          <Comment>For these reasons, this variant has been classified as Pathogenic. Algorithms developed to predict the effect of sequence changes on RNA splicing suggest that this variant may disrupt the consensus splice site. ClinVar contains an entry for this variant (Variation ID: 962403). Disruption of this splice site has been observed in individual(s) with clinical features of type VI collagenopathy (PMID: 29172004). In at least one individual the variant was observed to be de novo. This variant is not present in population databases (gnomAD no frequency). This sequence change affects a splice site in intron 9 of the COL6A2 gene. It is expected to disrupt RNA splicing. Variants that disrupt the donor or acceptor splice site typically lead to a loss of protein function (PMID: 16199547), and loss-of-function variants in COL6A2 are known to be disease-causing for autosomal recessive COL6A2 conditions (PMID: 21280092, 20976770). However, certain variants affecting donor or acceptor splice sites in the triple helical domain of COL6A2 are expected to result in in-frame exon skipping and have been reported to cause autosomal dominant COL6A2-related conditions (PMID: 18366090).</Comment>
